to import their events into external calendars (google calendar or iCal) without seeing an error message telling them “iCal (or other) can’t read this calendar file.”</p>\n<p>This issue has since been patched in the Events Calendar PRO 2.0.3 code and a hotfix deployed for any new downloads. If you experienced this issue, just re-download the 2.0.3 code and you&#8217;ll be all set. We apologize for the inconvenience along these lines and will make sure this doesn&#8217;t get reverted upon releasing 2.1.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:66:\"http://tri.be/fix-deployed-for-broken-webcal-import-in-2-0-3/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"2\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:44:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"How To Hide Events From Unregistered Users\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"http://tri.be/how-to-hide-events-from-unregistered-users/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:66:\"http://tri.be/how-to-hide-events-from-unregistered-users/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 26 Jan 2012 17:21:50 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Products\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Tutorial\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:22:\"http://tri.be/?p=14188\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:413:\"DISCLAIMER: This is a quick hack provided by a user, and not a foolproof solution. A determined visitor could still see all event data in the HTML markup, with Firebug or other browser dev tools, by viewing the page source or by turning off CSS in their browser. Google will also see the content. A foolproof method here would be done in full php and is beyond the scope of a simple tutorial. Users familiar [...]\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"Rob La Gatta\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3246:\"<p><em>DISCLAIMER: This is a quick hack provided by a user, and not a foolproof solution. A determined visitor could still see all event data in the HTML markup, with Firebug or other browser dev tools, by viewing the page source or by turning off CSS in their browser. Google will also see the content. A foolproof method here would be done in full php and is beyond the scope of a simple tutorial.</em></p>\n<p>Users familiar with the PRO forums will know that one of our more active threads over there is <a href=\"http://tri.be/support/forums/topic/what-tutorialshacks-would-you-like-to-see/\">this one</a>, where users propose tutorials/hacks they&#8217;d like to see published that could help extend Events Calendar PRO&#8217;s functionality. An interesting suggestion came through a few days from user <a href=\"http://tri.be/support/forums/users/maeda/\">Maeda</a>, who was wondering how to hide events from unregistered users.</p>\n<p>Before we had a chance to draft such a tutorial, the user came back with his own suggestion. Jonah and I fine tuned that today to turn it into the tutorial you&#8217;re about to read. Another big thanks to Maeda for his help!</p>\n<p>To hide your events from everyone but registered users, follow these simple steps:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>To start, create an event category called &#8220;Private.&#8221;</li>\n<li>Optionally install and configure the Members plugin to add your new roles. It can be snagged <a href=\"http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/members/\">right here</a>.</li>\n<li>Replace line 138 in views/table.php (make a duplicate copy in an &#8216;events&#8217; folder first), overwriting what&#8217;s currently there with this:<br />\n<code>&lt;div id=\'event_&lt;?php echo $eventId; ?&gt;\' &lt;?php if ( current_user_can(\'administrator\') ) {<br />\npost_class(\'tribe-events-event tribe-events-real-event\');<br />\n} else if( current_user_can(\'employee\') ) {<br />\npost_class(\'tribe-events-event tribe-events-real-event\');<br />\n} else {<br />\npost_class(\'tribe-events-event tribe-events-real-event hideme\');<br />\n} ?&gt;&gt;</code></li>\n<li>Swap out the &#8216;employee&#8217; role and/or add additional conditional roles for however many roles the user wants to use for this. You can optionally just leave out these extra role conditions and just check for the administrator role like so:<br />\n<code>&lt;div id=\'event_&lt;?php echo $eventId; ?&gt;\' &lt;?php if ( current_user_can(\'administrator\') ) {<br />\npost_class(\'tribe-events-event tribe-events-real-event\');<br />\n} else {<br />\npost_class(\'tribe-events-event tribe-events-real-event hideme\');<br />\n} ?&gt;&gt;<br />\n</code>^&#8211; All you&#8217;re doing here is conditionally setting the post_class function and you can assign any class(es) you want (i.e. &#8220;hideme&#8221; or other class you want to add) depending on role.</li>\n<li>Lastly, just add the CSS to hide the events div with:<br />\n<code>.cat_private.hideme {<br />\ndisplay: none;}</code></li>\n</ol>\n<p>That&#8217;s it! If you followed the steps above correctly, your events should now be restricted to only those with appropriate permissions to view them. If you&#8217;ve got any problems or are stuck trying to implement this approach, just let us know in the comments below.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:62:\"http://tri.be/how-to-hide-events-from-unregistered-users/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"2\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:34:\"How To Add Events to Your RSS Feed\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:49:\"