 weeks and interrupted almost all of its manufacturing in China.&nbsp; In 2011 it was reported that French supermarket Carrefour had not raised employees&rsquo; salaries for 12 consecutive years.&nbsp; This drew considerable attention from the local government in Shanghai and Carrefour was forced to raise wages by 8 percent after a Government-led collective negotiation with the employees.</p>\n<p>In addition, trade unions at different levels have been very active in urging employers to sign collectively bargained contracts that include salary increase as the main content.&nbsp; Furthermore, additional rules relating to the collective negotiation process have been issued to provide guidelines regarding collective negotiation for enterprises that do not have trade unions.&nbsp; The future for collective salary negotiation looks bright, but is that really the case?</p>\n<p>To read the full article, <a href=\"http://www.mwe.com/info/news/int-winter11.pdf#page=4\">click here</a>.&nbsp;</p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/MWE-EmployeeBenefitsBlog/~4/KmdrtIilzPA\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:68:\"http://feeds.lexblog.com/~r/MWE-EmployeeBenefitsBlog/~3/KmdrtIilzPA/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:126:\"http://www.employeebenefitsblog.com/2012/04/articles/employment/recent-developments-in-collective-salary-negotiation-in-china/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:9:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:24:\"China salary negotiation\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:6:\"domain\";s:40:\"http://www.employeebenefitsblog.com/tags\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_